<TABLE STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; FONT-SIZE:10PT" CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR HEIGHT=0 STYLE="FONT-SIZE:0">
<TD WIDTH=631.2 />
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; PADDING-BOTTOM:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=631.2>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=CENTER>
<B>
<U>
	OUTLOOK
</U>
</B>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=CENTER>
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="IHC4Q2015_10K_HTM_OLE_LINK31">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	For 2016, we anticipate:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	A decrease in premiums and earnings due to exiting the medical stop-loss business as a result of the closing of the Risk Solutions Sale and Coinsurance Transaction.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Continued significant increase in specialty health premiums (including short-term and supplemental health products, such as dental, accidental medical, gap and critical illness products), and continued decrease in major medical premiums, which is in run-off. Increasing emphasis on direct-to-consumer and career advisor distribution initiatives as we believe this will be a growing means for selling health insurance in the coming years, and accompanying start-up costs of expanding our sales through our call center, career model (including our newly launched Aspira A Mas outreach to the Hispanic community) and transactional websites.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Increasing retention in our group life and disability lines of business. In 2016, we expect a continuation of the increase in premiums from group long-term and short-term disability driven by higher retention amounts and a full year of premiums generated by a relatively new distribution partnership.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Continued evaluation of strategic transactions. &nbsp;As a result of the sale of Risk Solutions, we have significant cash. &nbsp;We plan to redeploy some of this cash in making investments and acquisitions to bolster existing or new lines of business. &nbsp;Specialty Benefits has made one such investment in a call center that will begin writing substantially all of its specialty health business with carriers affiliated with IHC. &nbsp;We are currently negotiating several similar transactions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Continued focus on administrative efficiencies, including a reduced operating loss at EHAE.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Initiating the process to take AMIC private.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	On March 31, 2016, IHC and its subsidiary Independence American Holdings Corp. sold the stock of Risk Solutions. &nbsp;In addition, under the purchase and sale agreement, all of the in-force stop-loss business of Standard Security Life and Independence American produced by Risk Solutions is co-insured by Westport as of January 1, 2016. &nbsp;The aggregate purchase price was $152.5 million in cash, subject to adjustments and settlements. &nbsp;This transaction resulted in a gain on the sale estimated at approximately $100 million. &nbsp;As a result, IHC is highly liquid and has excess capital; however its Medical Stop-Loss line of business will be in run-off, which will have a negative impact on future earnings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company will remain highly liquid in 2016 as a result of the continuing shorter duration of the portfolio. As a result, the yields on our investment portfolio were, and continue to remain, lower than in prior years and investment income may continue to be depressed for 2016. IHC has approximately $150.9 million in highly rated shorter maturity securities earning on average 1.2%; our portfolio as a whole is rated, on average, AA. The low duration of our portfolio enables us, if we deem prudent, the flexibility to reinvest in much higher yielding longer-term securities, which would significantly increase investment income in the future. &nbsp;A low duration portfolio such as ours also mitigates the adverse impact of potential inflation. &nbsp;IHC will continue to monitor the financial markets and invest accordingly.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Our results depend on the adequacy of our product pricing, our underwriting, the accuracy of our reserving methodology, returns on our invested assets, and our ability to manage expenses. &nbsp;We will also need to be diligent with the increased rate review scrutiny to effect timely rate changes and will need to stay focused on the management of medical cost drivers as medical trend levels cause margin pressures. &nbsp;Therefore, factors affecting these items, as well as unemployment and global financial markets, may have a material adverse effect on our results of operations and financial condition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage49"></A>
<P STYLE=PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;MARGIN-TOP:0;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-4PT;FONT-SIZE:4PT />
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; WIDTH:96PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	ITEM 7A.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT">
<B>
<U>
	QUANTITATIVE AND QUALITATIVE DISCLOSURES ABOUT
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:96PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<U>
	MARKET RISK
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company manages interest rate risk by seeking to maintain an investment portfolio with a duration and average life that falls within the band of the duration and average life of the applicable liabilities. Options may be utilized to modify the duration and average life of such assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The following summarizes the estimated pre-tax change in fair value (based upon hypothetical parallel shifts in the U.S. Treasury yield curve) of the fixed income portfolio (excluding redeemable preferred stocks) assuming immediate changes in interest rates at specified levels at December 31, 2015:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; FONT-SIZE:8PT">

<TD STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:9.6PX; PADDING-TOP:0PX; PADDING-RIGHT:9.6PX; PADDING-BOTTOM:0PX" VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=85.067>

</TABLE>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company monitors its investment portfolio on a continuous basis and believes that the liquidity of the Insurance Group will not be adversely affected by its current investments. This monitoring includes the maintenance of an asset-liability model that matches current insurance liability cash flows with current investment cash flows. This is accomplished by first creating an insurance model of the Company's in-force policies using current assumptions on mortality, lapses and expenses. Then, current investments are assigned to specific insurance blocks in the model using appropriate prepayment schedules and future reinvestment patterns.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The results of the model specify whether the investments and their related cash flows can support the related current insurance cash flows. Additionally, various scenarios are developed changing interest rates and other related assumptions. These scenarios help evaluate the market risk due to changing interest rates in relation to the business of the Insurance Group.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In the Company's analysis of the asset-liability model, a 100 to 200 basis point change in interest rates on the Insurance Group's liabilities would not be expected to have a material adverse effect on the Company. With respect to its liabilities, if interest rates were to increase, the risk to the Company is that policies would be surrendered and assets would need to be sold. This is not a material exposure to the Company since a large portion of the Insurance Group's interest sensitive policies are burial policies that are not subject to the typical surrender patterns of other interest sensitive policies, and many of the Insurance Group's universal life and annuity policies were acquired from liquidated companies which tend to exhibit lower surrender rates than such policies of continuing companies. Additionally, there are charges to help offset the benefits being surrendered. If interest rates were to decrease substantially, the risk to the Company is that some of its investment assets would be subject to early redemption. This is not a material exposure because the Company would have additional unrealized gains in its investment portfolio to help offset the future reduction of investment income. With respect to its investments, the Company employs (from time to time as warranted) investment strategies to mitigate interest rate and other market exposures.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>

<EFX_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES>
<A NAME="FIS_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<U>
	CONTROLS AND PROCEDURES
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Management&#146;s Report on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Management of the Company is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting as such term is defined in the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 (&#147;the Exchange Act&#148;) Rule 13a-15(f). The Company&#146;s internal controls are designed to provide reasonable assurance as to the reliability of its financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Due to inherent limitations, internal control over financial reporting may not prevent or detect misstatement. Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Management assessed the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2015, and in connection with this assessment, management
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:'CALIBRI,TIMES NEW ROMAN'">
</FONT>
	believes that the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting was not effective due to the material weaknesses in internal control over financial reporting described below. In making this assessment, management used the criteria set forth in the Internal Control &#150; Integrated Framework (2013) issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	On April 30, 2015, American Independence Corp, a consolidated subsidiary of the Company increased its ownership in Global Accident Facilities, LLC (&#147;GAF&#148;) from 40% to 80%. Management excluded from its assessment of internal control over financial reporting GAF&#146;s internal control over financial reporting. GAF constituted approximately 1.2% of total assets as of December 31, 2015, and approximately 0.6% of total revenues for the year ended December 31, 2015, which are included in the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements as of and for the year ended December 31, 2015. The Company will incorporate GAF into its assessment of internal control over financial reporting in 2016. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	A material weakness is a deficiency or combination of deficiencies in internal control over financial reporting such that there is a reasonable possibility that a material misstatement of the annual or interim financial statements will not be prevented or detected on a timely basis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	&nbsp;Management concluded that, as of December 31, 2015, the Company did not maintain an effective control environment, risk assessment process and process level controls over the financial reporting for income taxes. Specifically the Company:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Did not have sufficient tax accounting resources with adequate knowledge of the Company&#146;s process and controls over financial reporting related to income taxes to effectively design, operate, and document controls over accounting for income taxes;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Did not have an adequate risk assessment process related to income tax accounting to identify and appropriately account for income taxes associated with significant, non-routine transactions; and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage51"></A>
<P STYLE=PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;MARGIN-TOP:0;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-4PT;FONT-SIZE:4PT />
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Did not have effective process level controls over completeness, existence, accuracy and disclosure of deferred tax balances.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	These material weaknesses resulted in immaterial errors within the deferred tax balances in the Company&#146;s December 31, 2015 Consolidated Balance Sheet and in the Statements of Changes in Stockholders&#146; Equity for the three-year period ended December 31, 2015. The immaterial errors were corrected before the issuance of our December 31, 2015 Form 10-K, and these corrections had no impact on the Consolidated Statement of Income, the computations of basic and diluted earnings per share, the Consolidated Statements of Comprehensive Income or the Statements of Cash Flows for the years ended December 31, 2013, 2014 or 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2015, has been audited by KPMG LLP, an independent registered public accounting firm, as stated in their report which appears in Item 8 of this Form 10-K.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Remediation Plan
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company intends to take steps during 2016 to remediate its material weaknesses in internal control over financial reporting for income taxes. The Company has begun and will continue:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Augmenting existing tax staff with additional skilled tax accounting resources and providing additional training to existing staff on the design and operation of tax related financial reporting and corresponding internal controls;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Enhancing risk assessment processes that operate over accounting for income taxes, with a particular focus on the tax accounting and disclosure for unusual and complex transactions; and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Reviewing the processes and controls in place to measure and record transactions related to tax accounting to enhance the effectiveness of the design and operation of those controls.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Company has begun to implement the remediation efforts described above; however, until the remediation actions are fully implemented and the operational effectiveness of related internal controls validated through testing, the material weaknesses described above will continue to exist.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Evaluation of Disclosure Controls and Procedures
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	At the end of the period covered by this Annual Report on Form 10-K, we carried out an evaluation, under the supervision and with the participation of management, including the Chief Executive Office (&#147;CEO&#148;) and the Chief Financial Officer (&#147;CFO&#148;), of the effectiveness of our disclosure controls and procedures (as defined in Rules 13a-15(e) and 15d-15(e) under the Exchange Act). Based upon that evaluation, the identification of &nbsp;material weaknesses in our internal control over financial reporting for income taxes, as discussed in &#147;Management&#146;s Report on Internal Control over Financial Reporting&#148;, and our resulting inability to file this Annual Report on Form 10-K by March 15, 2016, our CEO and CFO have concluded our disclosure controls and procedures (as defined in Rule 13a-15(e) under the Exchange Act, as amended) were not effective to provide reasonable assurance that information required to be disclosed in the reports we file and submit under the Exchange Act is recorded, processed, summarized and reported within the time period specified in the SEC&#146;s rules and forms.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Changes in Internal Control Over Financial Reporting
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Our Management, including the CEO and CFO, identified no change in our internal control over financial reporting that occurred during our fiscal quarter ended December 31, 2015, that has materially affected or is reasonably likely to materially affect, our internal control over financial reporting.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage52"></A>
<P STYLE=PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;MARGIN-TOP:0;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-4PT;FONT-SIZE:4PT />

<B>
	ITEM 9B.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<U>
	OTHER INFORMATION
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	None.
</B>
</P>
</EFX_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES>

(&#147;Madison National Life&#148;), a wholly owned subsidiary of IHC; for more than the past five years, a director and President of Southern Life and Health Insurance Company, an insurance company and wholly owned subsidiary of &nbsp;Geneve Holdings, Inc., the controlling shareholder of IHC, with principal offices in Homewood, Alabama; for more than the past five years, a director of Standard Security Life Insurance Company of New York (&#147;Standard Security Life&#148;), a wholly owned subsidiary of IHC.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In furtherance of its longstanding goals of providing effective governance of IHC&#146;s business and affairs for the long-term benefit of stockholders and promoting a culture and reputation of the highest ethics, integrity and reliability, the Board has adopted:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	a Code of Business Ethics that applies to IHC&#146;s Chief Executive Officer and President, Chief Operating Officer, Chief Financial Officer, controller and other IHC employees performing similar functions (the &#147;Code of Ethics&#148;);
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	a Corporate Code of Conduct that applies to all employees, officers and directors of IHC and its subsidiaries and affiliates (the &#147;Code of Conduct&#148;);
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Corporate Governance Guidelines (&#147;Guidelines&#148;) to advance the functioning of the Board and its committees and set forth the Board&#146;s expectations as to how it should perform its functions; and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	written charters for its Audit and Compensation Committees of the Board (the &#147;Charters&#148;).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Code of Ethics, Code of Conduct, the Guidelines and the Charters can be found on IHC&#146;s website at www.ihcgroup.com, and are also available in print to any stockholder who requests them. &nbsp;The information on IHC&#146;s website, however, is not incorporated by reference in, and does not form part of, this annual report. &nbsp;The Board does not anticipate modifying the Code of Ethics or the Code of Conduct, or granting any waivers to either, but were any such waiver or modification to occur, it would promptly be disclosed on IHC&#146;s website. &nbsp;
</P>

<A NAME="IHC4Q2015_10K_HTM_130">
</A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Audit Committee Financial Expert
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Board has determined that at least one member of the Audit Committee, Mr. Tatum, is an audit committee financial expert as such term is defined in Item 407(d)(5)(ii) of Regulation S-K promulgated by the SEC.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Nomination of Director Candidates
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In light of GHI&#146;s majority voting power, the Board has determined that the Board, rather than a nominating committee, is the most appropriate body to identify director candidates and select nominees for presentation at the annual meeting of stockholders. &nbsp;In making nominations, the Board seeks candidates with outstanding business experience who will bring such experience to the management and direction of IHC. &nbsp;The minimum criteria employed by the Board in its selection of candidates, is set forth in the Guidelines, along with certain other factors that inform the selection process. &nbsp;All directors serving on the Board participate in the consideration of director nominees. &nbsp;Furthermore, in light of GHI&#146;s voting power, the Board has determined that no policy with respect to consideration of candidates recommended by security holders other than GHI&#146;s would be appropriate. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:624PX">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Audit Committee
</I>
</B>
<I>
	.
</I>
	&nbsp;The principal functions of the Audit Committee are to: (i) select an independent registered public accounting firm; (ii) review and approve management&#146;s plan for engaging IHC&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm during the year to perform non-audit services and consider what effect these services will have on the independence of IHC&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm; (iii) review IHC&#146;s annual financial statements and other financial reports which require approval by the Board; (iv) oversee the integrity of IHC&#146;s financial statements, IHC&#146;s systems of disclosure controls and internal controls over financial reporting and IHC&#146;s compliance with legal and regulatory requirements; (v) review the scope of audit plans of IHC&#146;s internal audit function and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage56"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	independent registered public accounting firm and the results of their audits; and (vi) evaluate the performance of IHC&#146;s internal audit function and independent registered public accounting firm.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Each member of the Audit Committee meets the independence requirements of the NYSE and applicable SEC rules and regulations. &nbsp;The Audit Committee and the Board have determined that each member of the Audit Committee is financially literate and that Mr. Tatum qualifies as an &#147;audit committee financial expert,&#148; as such term is defined in Item 401(h)(2) of Regulation S-K promulgated by the SEC.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Compensation Committee
</I>
</B>
<I>
	.
</I>
	&nbsp;The Compensation Committee assists the Board in fulfilling its responsibilities with regard to compensation matters, is responsible for determining or ratifying (as the case may be) the compensation of IHC&#146;s executive officers and administers IHC&#146;s 2006 Stock Incentive Plan. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee has sole authority to determine the compensation for IHC&#146;s Chief Executive Officer and President.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Involvement in Certain Legal Proceedings
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Our directors and executive officers have not been involved in any of the following events during the past ten years:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:72PX; WIDTH:96PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	1.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:96PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	any bankruptcy petition filed by or against such person or any business of which such person was a general partner or executive officer either at the time of the bankruptcy or within two years prior to that time;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:72PX; WIDTH:96PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	2.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:96PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	any conviction in a criminal proceeding or being subject to a pending criminal proceeding (excluding traffic violations and other minor offenses);
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:72PX; WIDTH:96PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	3.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:96PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	being subject to any order, judgment, or decree, not subsequently reversed, suspended or vacated, of any court of competent jurisdiction, permanently or temporarily enjoining him from or otherwise limiting his involvement in any type of business, securities or banking activities or to be associated with any person practicing in banking or securities activities;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:72PX; WIDTH:96PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	4.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:96PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	being found by a court of competent jurisdiction in a civil action, the Securities and Exchange Commission or the Commodity Futures Trading Commission to have violated a federal or state securities or commodities law, and the judgment has not been reversed, suspended, or vacated;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:72PX; WIDTH:96PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	5.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:96PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	being subject of, or a party to, any federal or state judicial or administrative order, judgment decree, or finding, not subsequently reversed, suspended or vacated, relating to an alleged violation of any federal or state securities or commodities law or regulation, any law or regulation respecting financial institutions or insurance companies, or any law or regulation prohibiting mail or wire fraud or fraud in connection with any business entity; or
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:72PX; WIDTH:96PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	6.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:96PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	being subject of or party to any sanction or order, not subsequently reversed, suspended, or vacated, of any self-regulatory organization, any registered entity or any equivalent exchange, association, entity or organization that has disciplinary authority over its members or persons associated with a member.
</P>
</EFX_DIRECTORS_AND_OFFICERS>

<A NAME="eolPage57"></A>
<P STYLE=PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;MARGIN-TOP:0;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-4PT;FONT-SIZE:4PT />
<EFX_COMPENSATION>
<A NAME="FIS_COMPENSATION"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; WIDTH:96PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
<B>
	ITEM 11.
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<U>
	EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Compensation Discussion and Analysis
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<B>
<I>
	&#147;Say-on- Pay&#148; and &#147;Say-on-Frequency&#148;
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Compensation Committee considered the voting results of the advisory, non-binding &#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote at IHC&#146;s 2014 Annual Meeting of Stockholders in connection with the discharge of its responsibilities. &nbsp;IHC&#146;s stockholders expressed their support of the compensation for our CEO, CFO and the three other most-highly compensated officers in respect of 2013, with a substantial majority of the votes cast voting to approve the compensation of IHC&#146;s named executive officers described in IHC&#146;s 2014 proxy statement. &nbsp;Following the Compensation Committee&#146;s review and consideration of this stockholder support, as well as the other factors discussed in more detail below, we determined to make no changes to our approach to executive compensation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	At IHC&#146;s 2011 Annual Meeting of Stockholders, a majority of IHC&#146;s stockholders voted for &#147;say-on-pay&#148; proposals to occur every three years. &nbsp;In light of this voting result on the frequency of &#147;say-on-pay&#148; proposals, the Board decided that IHC will present &#147;say-on-pay&#148; proposals every three years until the next required vote on the frequency of stockholder votes on named executive officer compensation. &nbsp;Accordingly, we held such a vote at our 2014 Annual Meeting of Stockholders and we currently expect to hold the next &#147;say-on-pay&#148; vote at IHC&#146;s 2017 Annual Meeting of Stockholders. &nbsp;We currently expect the next stockholder vote on the frequency of stockholder votes on named executive officer compensation to also occur at IHC&#146;s 2017 Annual Meeting of Stockholders.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Compensation Objectives
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Compensation of each of IHC&#146;s executive officers is intended to be based on performance of IHC and the executive. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee has responsibility for establishing and reviewing the compensation of IHC&#146;s CEO and for reviewing the compensation for all of IHC&#146;s executive officers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	In establishing executive officer compensation, the following are among the Compensation Committee&#146;s objectives:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:37.467PX; WIDTH:61.467PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.8PX; PADDING-LEFT:61.467PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	attract and retain individuals of superior ability and managerial talent;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:37.467PX; WIDTH:61.467PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.8PX; PADDING-LEFT:61.467PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	ensure compensation is aligned with IHC&#146;s corporate strategies, business objectives and the long-term interests of IHC&#146;s stockholders; and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:37.467PX; WIDTH:61.467PX; FONT-FAMILY:'SYMBOL'; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#183;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.8PX; PADDING-LEFT:61.467PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	enhance incentives to increase IHC&#146;s stock price and maximize stockholder value by providing a portion of total compensation in IHC equity and equity-related instruments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	IHC&#146;s overall compensation program is structured to attract, motivate and retain highly qualified executive officers by paying them competitively, consistent with IHC&#146;s success and their contributions to such success. &nbsp;To this end, base salary and bonus are designed to reward annual achievements and to be commensurate with an executive&#146;s scope of responsibilities, demonstrated leadership abilities and management experience and effectiveness. &nbsp;Other elements of compensation focus on motivating and challenging IHC&#146;s executive officers to achieve superior, long-term, sustained results.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	Implementation of Objectives
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<U>
	Salaries
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The salary of an IHC executive officer is based on his or her level of responsibility, experience and qualifications and recent performance. &nbsp;Adjustments to salary are made in response to changes in any of the foregoing factors and changes in market conditions. &nbsp;Executive officer salaries are typically reviewed by the Compensation Committee every twelve months. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee has sole
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage58"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	authority to determine the compensation for IHC&#146;s Chief Executive Officer. &nbsp;Neither the Compensation Committee nor IHC has retained a compensation consultant or similar organization for assistance in reviewing or setting executive officer salaries or other compensation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<U>
	Cash Bonuses
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Following the close of each fiscal year, IHC&#146;s Chief Executive Officer and President makes determinations that are communicated to the Compensation Committee as to cash bonuses for IHC&#146;s executive officers (excluding himself), based on an analysis of: (i) any contractual commitments set forth in an employment agreement; (ii) IHC&#146;s performance in the year ended versus IHC&#146;s plan for such year; and (iii) a subjective evaluation of a variety of factors as to each executive officer&#146;s individual contribution during the year. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee then convenes outside the presence of the Chief Executive Officer and President and, following appropriate deliberation, approves or ratifies bonuses for all IHC executive officers. &nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The salaries paid and annual bonuses awarded to IHC&#146;s named executive officers in respect of 2015 are set forth in the Summary Compensation Table.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<U>
	Equity Awards
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	IHC&#146;s 2006 Stock Incentive Plan (the &#147;2006 Plan&#148;) provided the opportunity for the Compensation Committee to make equity incentive awards to, among others, IHC&#146;s executive officers. While there are outstanding grants under the 2006 Plan, it has expired and no new grants may be made under it. &nbsp;The Board of Directors has approved a 2016 Stock Incentive Plan (the &#147;2016 Plan&#148;) on substantially the same terms as the 2006 Plan, and it will be submitted for shareholder approval at the next meeting of shareholders, which is expected to be held later this year. The following describes the 2016 Plan and is largely consistent with the 2006 Plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	&nbsp;The types of equity awards that may be granted under the 2016 Plan are: &nbsp;(i) options; (ii) share appreciation rights (&#147;SARs&#148;); (iii) restricted shares, restricted share units (which are shares granted after certain vesting conditions are met) and unrestricted shares; (iv) deferred share units; and (v) performance awards. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee determines the type and amount of the award with reference to factors that include the present value of the award relative to the executive officer&#146;s salary and anticipated cash bonus, the anticipated importance of the executive&#146;s position to IHC&#146;s future results, and the size of the executive&#146;s total compensation relative both to other executives within IHC and to compensation levels at other companies. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Within the limitations of the 2016 Plan, the Compensation Committee may modify an award to: (i) accelerate the rate at which an option or SAR may be exercised (including, without limitation, permitting an option or SAR to be exercised in full without regard to the installment or vesting provisions or whether the option or SAR is at the time exercisable); (ii) accelerate the vesting of any award; (iii) extend or renew outstanding awards; or (iv) accept the cancellation of outstanding awards. &nbsp;However, the Compensation Committee may not, without stockholder approval, cancel an outstanding option that is underwater for the purpose of reissuing the option to a grantee within six months thereafter at a lower exercise price, or granting a replacement award of a different type. &nbsp;Notwithstanding the foregoing provision, no modification of an outstanding award can materially and adversely affect a grantee&#146;s rights thereunder, unless the grantee provides written consent, there is an express 2016 Plan provision permitting the Compensation Committee to act unilaterally to make the modification, or the Compensation Committee reasonably concludes that the modification is not materially adverse to the grantee.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Options
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Incentive stock options (&#147;ISOs&#148;) and non-incentive stock options (&#147;Non-ISOs&#148;) may be granted under the 2016 Plan. &nbsp;At the sole discretion of the Compensation Committee, any option may be
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage59"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	exercisable, in whole or in part, immediately upon the grant thereof, or only after the occurrence of a specified event, or only in installments, which installments may vary. &nbsp;The term of any option may not exceed ten years from the grant date;
<I>
	provided, however,
</I>
	that in the case of an ISO granted to an employee of IHC or any of its affiliates who owns stock representing more than ten percent (10%) of the voting stock on the grant date (&#147;Employee Ten Percent Holder&#148;), the term of the ISO shall not exceed five years from the grant date. &nbsp;The exercise price of an option is determined by the Compensation Committee in its sole discretion;
<I>
	provided, however,
</I>
	that if an ISO is granted to an Employee Ten Percent Holder (as defined in the Plan), the per share exercise price shall not be less than 110% of the closing price per share on the NYSE on the grant date (&#147;Fair Market Value&#148;); and
<I>
	provided further
</I>
	that for all other options, the per share exercise price shall not be less than 100% of the Fair Market Value on the grant date. &nbsp;Neither IHC nor the Compensation Committee can allow for a repricing without stockholder approval.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Each of IHC&#146;s named executive officers holds stock options, having varying exercise prices and expiration dates (based on the date granted). &nbsp;Please see the information set forth in the tables below for additional information. &nbsp;IHC does not have a target level of stock ownership applicable to any of its employees, including the named executive officers. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Share Appreciation Rights (SARs)
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Compensation Committee may grant SARs either concurrently with the grant of an option or with respect to an outstanding option (in which case the SAR will extend to all or a portion of the shares covered by the related option, the exercise price is the same as the exercise price of the related option, and the SAR is exercisable at such time or times, and to the extent, that the related option will be exercisable), or independent of any option. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee may also grant SARs that are exercisable only upon or in respect of a change in control (as defined in the Plan) or any other specified event. &nbsp;The per share exercise price of a SAR cannot be less than 100% of the Fair Market Value, and the SARs may only be exercised when the Fair Market Value of the shares underlying the SAR exceeds the exercise price of the SAR. &nbsp;Neither IHC nor the Compensation Committee can allow for a repricing without stockholder approval. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Restricted Shares, Restricted Share Units and Unrestricted Shares
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Subject to applicable law, an award of 2,475 restricted shares (or such other amount that the Board may determine on a prospective basis) will be granted to each non-employee director of IHC on the date immediately following each annual meeting of IHC&#146;s stockholders. &nbsp;One-third of those restricted shares will vest on each of the next three annual anniversaries of the date the restricted shares were awarded. &nbsp;In the event that a non-employee director terminates his or her membership on the Board for any reason, the director will immediately forfeit any unvested restricted shares.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	At any time within the thirty-day period (or other shorter or longer period that the Compensation Committee selects in its sole discretion) in which a grantee who is a member of a select group of management or highly compensated employees receives an initial award of either restricted shares or restricted share units, the Compensation Committee may permit the grantee to irrevocably elect to defer the receipt of all or a percentage of the shares that would otherwise be transferred to the grantee upon the vesting of such award.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Deferred Share Units
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Compensation Committee may permit any director, consultant or member of a select group of management or highly compensated employees to irrevocably elect to forego the receipt of cash or other compensation (including shares), and in lieu thereof to have IHC credit to an internal Plan account a number of deferred share units having a Fair Market Value equal to the shares and other compensation deferred.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage60"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<I>
	Performance Awards
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Compensation Committee may grant a performance award based on one or more of the following to measure IHC, affiliate, and/or business unit performance during a specified performance period: (i) gross or net premiums; (ii) profit margin; (iii) insured lives; (iv) basic, diluted, or adjusted earnings per share; (v) sales or revenue; (vi) earnings before interest, taxes, and other adjustments (in total or on a per share basis); (vii) basic or adjusted net income; (viii) returns on equity, assets, capital, revenue or similar measure; (ix) economic value added; (x) working capital; (xi) total stockholder return; and (xii) product development, product market share, research, licensing, litigation, human resources, information services, mergers, acquisitions, or sales of assets of affiliates or business units. Performance measures may vary from performance period to performance period and from grantee to grantee.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	A grantee will be eligible to receive payment in respect of a performance award only to the extent that the performance measure(s) for such award is achieved, and it is determined that all or some portion of such grantee&#146;s award has been earned for the performance period. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee reviews whether, and to what extent, the performance measure(s) for a particular performance period (of not less than one fiscal year) have been achieved and, if so, determines the amount of the performance award to be paid. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee may use negative discretion to decrease, but not increase, the amount of the award otherwise payable based upon such performance. &nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	At any time prior to the date that is at least six months before the close of a performance period (or shorter or longer period that the Compensation Committee selects), the Compensation Committee may permit a grantee who is a member of a select group of management or highly compensated employees to irrevocably elect to defer the receipt of all or a percentage of the cash or shares that would otherwise be transferred to the grantee upon the vesting of a performance award.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<U>
	Termination, Rescission and Recapture of Awards
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Each award under the Plan granted to an employee is intended to align such employee&#146;s long-term interest with those of IHC. &nbsp;Therefore, if the employee discloses confidential or proprietary information of IHC, provides services to a competitor of IHC, solicits a non-administrative employee of IHC, or has engaged in activities which conflict with IHC&#146;s interests (including any breaches of fiduciary duty or the duty of loyalty), the employee is acting contrary to IHC&#146;s long-term interests. &nbsp;Accordingly, except as otherwise expressly provided in an award agreement, IHC may terminate any outstanding, unexercised, unexpired, unpaid, or deferred awards, rescind any exercise, payment or delivery pursuant to the award, or recapture any common stock (whether restricted or unrestricted) or proceeds from the employee&#146;s sale of shares issued pursuant to the award. &nbsp;Notwithstanding the foregoing, IHC may, in its sole and absolute discretion, choose not to terminate, rescind or recapture upon the occurrence of any of the foregoing events.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<U>
	Tax Implications
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act amended the Tax Code to add Section 162(m)(6), which limits the amount that certain health care insurers, including the Company, may deduct for tax years starting after 2012. Section 162(m)(6) limits the tax deduction to $500,000 per individual, and makes no exception for performance-based compensation or commissions. In addition, the limit applies to compensation, including deferred compensation, paid to all current and former employees and most independent contractors, not just to compensation paid to a narrow group of current top executives. The rule became effective for employer tax years beginning after December 31, 2012. Consequently, the Company is limited to a $500,000 deduction for compensation paid to each named executive officer.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	&nbsp;Section 162(m)(1) of the Tax Code limits the amount a publicly-held corporation may deduct for compensation paid to the CEO and certain named executive officers to $1 million per year per executive, makes an exception for performance-based compensation and commissions, and excludes the compensation paid to former covered executives once they are no longer covered. Since the Company is
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage61"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	subject to Section 162(m)(6), the performance-based exclusion available under Section 162(m)(1) is not available to the Company.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:14.667PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Compensation Committee Report
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:9.8PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The Compensation Committee assists the Board in fulfilling its responsibilities with regard to compensation matters, and is responsible for establishing and approving the compensation of IHC&#146;s executive officers. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee has sole authority to determine the compensation for IHC&#146;s Chief Executive Officer. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee has reviewed and discussed the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; section of this Form 10-K with management, including our Chief Executive Officer and our Chief Financial Officer. &nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:60PX; WIDTH:84PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(1)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Represents strategic and long term incentive earnings as a result of Mr. Thung&#146;s Employment Agreement with IHC for the year indicated. IHC is party to the Officer Employment Agreement by and between IHC and Mr. Roy T.K. Thung, IHC&#146;s Chief Executive Officer, President and Chairman of the Board of Directors, dated as of May 11, 2011. Under the agreement, Mr. Thung is entitled to an incentive payment upon the disposition of a strategic asset of IHC equal to 3% of the amount above which the consideration received by IHC for such disposition exceeds the book value of such asset as of March 31, 2011. &nbsp;In addition, any termination of the agreement other than for &#147;cause&#148; triggers an incentive payment to Mr. Thung in respect of such appreciation in the overall book value of IHC. &nbsp;The initial term of Mr. Thung&#146;s employment agreement was two years from the date it was entered into, but, by its terms, will be automatically extended for successive two-year periods unless one hundred twenty days&#146; prior notice of non-renewal is given by IHC. In accordance with the terms of the agreement, Mr. Thung received a cash incentive payment of $288,728 in 2015 as a result of the coinsurance and sale transaction with National Guardian Life Insurance Company on July 31, 2015. Had the strategic and long-term incentive provisions of Mr. Thung&#146;s agreement been triggered on December 31, 2015, Mr. Thung would have received $2,370,272.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:60PX; WIDTH:84PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(2)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Represents the modification of fully vested options during 2014 to extend their expiration date. &nbsp;The amount reported is the incremental fair value of the modified award as of the modification date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:60PX; WIDTH:84PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(3)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Represents the modification of fully vested options during 2013 to extend their expiration date and impose a new, two-year vesting period. &nbsp;The amount reported is the incremental fair value of the modified award as of the modification date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:60PX; WIDTH:84PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	(4)
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:84PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Represents the increase (decrease) in the value of Mr. Thung&#146;s Retirement Benefits Agreement with IHC for the year indicated. Refer to Potential Payments to Named Executive Officers for additional information regarding this agreement.

<A NAME="eolPage64"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Potential Payments to Named Executive Officers
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	With Mr. Thung
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	IHC is party to a Retirement Benefits Agreement with Mr. Roy T.K. Thung, dated as of September 30, 1991, and amended by amendments dated as of December 20, 2002, June 17, 2005 and December 31, 2008, respectively, pursuant to which Mr. Thung is entitled to a lump-sum cash payment upon a &#147;separation from service&#148; from IHC of $1,659,557, increasing on a cumulative, compounding basis of 6% per annum from December 31, 2008. &nbsp;&#147;Separation from service&#148; is as defined under U.S. Treasury Regulations 1.409A-1(h)(1), and would generally include Mr. Thung&#146;s death, retirement or any other termination of employment, including permanent disability. For example, had this provision been triggered on December 31, 2015, Mr. Thung would have been entitled to receive a payment of $2,495,360.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	IHC is party to the Officer Employment Agreement by and between IHC and Mr. Roy T.K. Thung, IHC&#146;s Chief Executive Officer, President and Chairman of the Board of Directors, dated as of May 11, 2011. &nbsp;Under this employment agreement, if Mr. Thung&#146;s employment by IHC or its affiliate were to cease under certain circumstances, Mr. Thung would be entitled to receive a lump-sum severance amount equal to the average annual aggregate total compensation received by Mr. Thung during the preceding five years, adjusted
<I>
	pro rata
</I>
	for the applicable severance period. &nbsp;The applicable severance period would be the longer of: (i) twelve months; and (ii) a number of months equal to the aggregate number of years of service of Mr. Thung to IHC and its affiliates. &nbsp;The circumstances under which such severance would be paid are: (i) Mr. Thung&#146;s employment by IHC being involuntarily terminated under circumstances that would not constitute &#147;cause&#148; (examples of &#147;cause&#148; being Mr. Thung&#146;s material failure to follow IHC&#146;s lawful directions, material failure to follow IHC&#146;s corporate policies, breach of the non-compete covenants in the employment agreement or his engaging in unlawful behavior that would damage IHC or its reputation); (ii) such employment being voluntarily terminated under circumstances that would constitute &#147;good reason&#148; (examples of &#147;good reason&#148; being in connection with IHC&#146;s &nbsp;material breach of its obligations under the employment agreement, IHC&#146;s non-renewal of the employment agreement or change in control of IHC or its ultimate parent); or; (iii) upon Mr. Thung&#146;s death or permanent disability. &nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, under the agreement, Mr. Thung is also entitled to strategic and long-term incentive payments which are included in the Summary Compensation Table above. The initial term of Mr. Thung&#146;s employment agreement is two years from the date it was entered into, but, by its terms, it will be automatically extended for successive two-year periods unless one hundred twenty days&#146; prior notice of non-renewal is given by IHC. &nbsp;For example, had the severance provisions of Mr. Thung&#146;s agreement been triggered on December 31, 2015, Mr. Thung would have been entitled to receive approximately $64,961 per month for thirty-nine months (approximately $2,533,479 in the aggregate).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	With Ms. Herbert
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	IHC is party to the Officer Employment Agreement, by and between IHC and Ms. Teresa A. Herbert, IHC&#146;s Chief Financial Officer and Senior Vice President, dated as of April 18, 2011. &nbsp;Under this employment agreement, if Ms. Herbert&#146;s employment by IHC or its affiliate were to cease under certain circumstances, Ms. Herbert would be entitled to receive a severance amount equal to the average annual aggregate total compensation received by Ms. Herbert during the preceding five years, adjusted
<I>
	pro rata
</I>
	for the applicable severance period. &nbsp;The applicable severance period would be the longer of: (i) twelve months; and (ii) a number of months equal to the aggregate number of years of service of Ms. Herbert to IHC and its affiliates, not to exceed twenty-four months. &nbsp;The circumstances under which such severance would be paid are (i) Ms. Herbert&#146;s employment by IHC being involuntarily terminated under circumstances that would not constitute &#147;cause&#148; (examples of &#147;cause&#148; being Ms. Herbert&#146;s material failure to follow IHC&#146;s lawful directions, material failure to follow IHC&#146;s corporate policies, breach of the non-compete covenants in the employment agreement or her engaging in unlawful behavior that would damage IHC or its reputation), or (ii) such employment being voluntarily terminated under circumstances that would constitute &#147;good reason&#148; (examples of &#147;good reason&#148; being in connection with IHC&#146;s (or its
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage65"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	successor&#146;s) material breach of its obligations under the employment agreement or upon IHC&#146;s non-renewal of the employment agreement). &nbsp;The initial term of Ms. Herbert&#146;s employment agreement is two years from the date it was entered into, but, by its terms, it will be automatically extended for successive two-year periods unless one hundred twenty days&#146; prior notice of non-renewal is given by IHC. &nbsp;For example, had the severance provision in Ms. Herbert&#146;s agreement been triggered on December 31, 2015, Ms. Herbert would have been entitled to receive approximately $36,340 per month for twenty-four months ($872,160 in the aggregate).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	With Mr. Kettig
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	IHC is party to the Officer Employment Agreement, by and among IHC, Standard Security Life, and Mr. David T. Kettig, IHC&#146;s Chief Operating Officer, Executive Vice President and Acting General Counsel, dated as of April 18, 2011. &nbsp;Under this employment agreement, if Mr. Kettig&#146;s employment by SSL or its affiliate were to cease under certain circumstances, Mr. Kettig would be entitled to receive a severance amount equal to the average annual aggregate total compensation received by Mr. Kettig during the preceding five years, adjusted
<I>
	pro rata
</I>
	for the applicable severance period. &nbsp;The applicable severance period would be the longer of: (i) twelve months; and (ii) a number of months equal to the aggregate number of years of service of Mr. Kettig to IHC and its affiliates, not to exceed twenty-four months. &nbsp;The circumstances under which such severance would be paid are (i) Mr. Kettig&#146;s employment by SSL being involuntarily terminated under circumstances that would not constitute &#147;cause&#148; (examples of &#147;cause&#148; being Mr. Kettig&#146;s material failure to follow SSL&#146;s or IHC&#146;s lawful directions, material failure to follow SSL&#146;s or IHC&#146;s corporate policies, breach of the non-compete covenants in the employment agreement or his engaging in unlawful behavior that would damage SSL, IHC or their respective reputations), or (ii) such employment being voluntarily terminated under circumstances that would constitute &#147;good reason&#148; (examples of &#147;good reason&#148; being in connection with SSL&#146;s (or its successor&#146;s) material breach of its obligations under the employment agreement or upon SSL&#146;s non-renewal of the employment agreement). &nbsp;&nbsp;The initial term of Mr. Kettig&#146;s employment agreement is two years from the date it was entered into, but, by its terms, it will be automatically extended for successive two-year periods unless one hundred twenty days&#146; prior notice of non-renewal is given by SSL. &nbsp;For example, had the severance provision in Mr. Kettig&#146;s agreement been triggered on December&nbsp;31, 2015, Mr. Kettig would have been entitled to receive approximately $48,576 per month for twenty-four months ($1,165,824 in the aggregate).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	With Mr. Kemp
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	IHC was party to the Officer Employment Agreement, by and among IHC, Risk Solutions, and Mr. Michael Kemp, IHC&#146;s Chief Underwriting Officer and Senior Vice President, dated as of May 22, 2012. &nbsp;Under this employment agreement, if Mr. Kemp&#146;s employment by Risk Solutions or its affiliate were to cease under certain circumstances, Mr. Kemp would be entitled to receive a severance amount equal to the average annual aggregate total compensation received by Mr. Kemp during the preceding five years, adjusted
<I>
	pro rata
</I>
	for the applicable severance period. &nbsp;The applicable severance period would be the longer of: (i) twelve months; and (ii) 3.5 plus a number of months equal to the aggregate number of years of service of Mr. Kemp to IHC and its affiliates, not to exceed twenty-four months. &nbsp;The circumstances under which such severance would be paid were (i) Mr. Kemp&#146;s employment by Risk Solutions being involuntarily terminated under circumstances that would not constitute &#147;cause&#148; (examples of &#147;cause&#148; being Mr. Kemp&#146;s material failure to follow Risk Solutions&#146; or IHC&#146;s lawful directions, material failure to follow Risk Solutions&#146; or IHC&#146;s corporate policies, breach of the non-compete covenants in the employment agreement or his engaging in unlawful behavior that would damage Risk Solutions, IHC or their respective reputations), or (ii) such employment being voluntarily terminated under circumstances that would constitute &#147;good reason&#148; (examples of &#147;good reason&#148; being in connection with Risk Solutions&#146; (or its successor&#146;s) material breach of its obligations under the employment agreement or upon Risk Solutions&#146; non-renewal of the employment agreement). &nbsp;&nbsp;The severance provision in Mr. Kemp&#146;s agreement was triggered on March 31, 2016 with the sale of Risk Solutions and Mr. Kemp was paid a lump sum of $598,473.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:12.2PX">
<BR>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
<I>
	With Mr. Graber
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	IHC is party to the Officer Employment Agreement, by and among IHC, Madison National Life, and Mr. Larry R. Graber, IHC&#146;s Chief Life and Annuity Actuary and Senior Vice President, dated as of April 18, 2011. &nbsp;Under this employment agreement, if Mr. Graber&#146;s employment by MNL or its affiliate were to cease under certain circumstances, Mr.&nbsp;Graber would be entitled to receive a severance amount equal to the average annual aggregate total compensation received by Mr. Graber during the preceding five years, adjusted
<I>
	pro rata
</I>
	for the applicable severance period. &nbsp;The applicable severance period would be the longer of: (i) twelve months; and (ii) a number of months equal to the aggregate number of years of service of Mr. Graber to IHC and its affiliates, not to exceed twenty-four months. &nbsp;The circumstances under which such severance would be paid are (i) Mr. Graber&#146;s employment by MNL being involuntarily terminated under circumstances that would not constitute &#147;cause&#148; (examples of &#147;cause&#148; being Mr. Graber&#146;s material failure to follow MNL&#146;s or IHC&#146;s lawful directions, material failure to follow MNL&#146;s or IHC&#146;s corporate policies, breach of the non-compete covenants in the employment agreement or his engaging in unlawful behavior that would damage MNL, IHC or their respective reputations), or (ii) such employment being voluntarily terminated under circumstances that would constitute &#147;good reason&#148; (examples of &#147;good reason&#148; being in connection with MNL&#146;s (or its successor&#146;s) material breach of its obligations under the employment agreement or upon MNL&#146;s non-renewal of the employment agreement). &nbsp;&nbsp;The initial term of Mr. Graber&#146;s employment agreement is two years from the date it was entered into, but, by its terms, it will be automatically extended for successive two-year periods unless one hundred twenty days&#146; prior notice of non-renewal is given by MNL. &nbsp;For example, had the severance provision in Mr. Graber&#146;s agreement been triggered on December&nbsp;31, 2015, Mr. Graber would have been entitled to receive approximately $37,057 per month for nineteen months ($704,083 in the aggregate).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<B>
	Stock Incentive Plans
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	Under the terms of IHC&#146;s stock incentive plans, the Compensation Committee is obligated to make appropriate provision for the holders of awards thereunder in the event of a change in control of IHC or similar event. &nbsp;The specifics of such an occurrence cannot be anticipated, and thus the prospective effect upon IHC cannot reliably be quantified.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>

<A NAME="eolPage67"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS" ALIGN=CENTER>
<B>
	DIRECTORS&#146; COMPENSATION
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX">
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The general policy of the Board is that compensation for independent directors should be a mix of cash and equity. &nbsp;IHC does not pay management directors for board service in addition to their regular employee compensation. &nbsp;The Compensation Committee has the primary responsibility for reviewing and considering any revisions to director compensation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	During 2016, each non-employee (outside) director will be paid:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#149;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	an annual retainer of $36,000;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#149;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	$1,500 for each board or committee meeting attended;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#149;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	$9,000 for service as chairman of a board committee; and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PX; MARGIN-BOTTOM:-2PX; TEXT-INDENT:24PX; WIDTH:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT; CLEAR:LEFT; FLOAT:LEFT">
	&#149;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; PADDING-LEFT:48PX; TEXT-INDENT:-2PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	2,475 restricted shares of IHC common stock, vesting ratably over the three annual anniversaries of the award, and contingent upon continuing service as a director.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; CLEAR:LEFT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX; TEXT-INDENT:48PX; FONT-SIZE:11PT" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
	The following table summarizes compensation paid to IHC&#146;s directors during 2015 except for Mr. Roy T.K. Thung, IHC&#146;s Chief Executive Officer and President, Mr. David T. Kettig, Chief Operating Officer, Executive Vice President and Acting General Counsel, and Mr. Larry R. Graber, Chief Life and Annuity Actuary and Senior Vice President, for whom compensation was previously discussed.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PX" ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
<BR>
</P>
